│ 4, 5, 6, -1, -1, -1, -1, 7, -1, -1, -1, -1}\n- PoisonMaskElem = -1\n\nAt    │
│ index 11, CommonMask[11] = 11 (not -1) but SubVectorsMask[11] = 7 (not -1), │
│ which violates the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n\nThe log shows │
│ that the SLP vectorizer is attempting to vectorize a complex bundle of 16   │
│ icmp instructions followed by XOR reduction operations. The vectorizer      │
│ identifies this as a horizontal reduction pattern and tries to create a     │
│ shuffle-based cost estimation. The issue arises when trying to merge        │
│ subvector masks with the common mask during cost calculation.\n\nThe        │
│ problem is that the SubVectorsMask already has valid indices in positions   │
│ where the CommonMask also has valid indices, which shouldn't happen         │
│ according to the current assertion logic.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe │
│ root cause is in the logic that constructs the SVMask (SubVector Mask) for  │
│ cost estimation. The current code assumes that SubVectorsMask and           │
│ CommonMask should be disjoint - where CommonMask has valid indices,         │
│ SubVectorsMask should have poison elements (-1). However, in complex        │
│ reduction patterns with mixed operations, this assumption can be            │
│ violated.\n\nLooking at the code in lines 10923-10928, the algorithm        │
│ iterates through both masks and when it finds a valid element in CommonMask │
│ (I2 != PoisonMaskElem), it expects the corresponding SubVectorsMask element │
│ (I1) to be poison. But this assumption is too strict - there can be         │
│ legitimate cases where both masks have valid entries.\n\nThe fix is to      │
│ modify the logic to handle the case where both masks have valid entries by  │
│ prioritizing one over the other or merging them appropriately, rather than  │
│ asserting.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe issue is in the loop that   │
│ processes SVMask and CommonMask. Instead of asserting that I1 must be       │
│ PoisonMaskElem when I2 is not, we should handle the case where both are     │
│ valid. The most appropriate fix is to only update I1 when it is currently   │
│ poison, preserving any existing valid mapping in the subvector mask.\n\n5.  │
│ Conclusion:\n\nThe fix changes the assertion to a conditional update,       │
│ allowing the code to handle cases where both masks have valid entries. This │
│ prevents the crash while maintaining correct cost estimation behavior. The  │
│ modified logic will only overwrite SubVectorsMask entries that are          │
│ currently poison, preserving any existing valid mappings."})                │
